## Terms of Service

## Overview
Create a dedicated Terms of Service page that communicates the platform’s terms of use, governing law, liability limitations, and service-level notes. This page should be a readable, legally compliant, and visually consistent component within the Archject product. It must support future localization, easy updates by non-technical staff, and clear presentation of the acceptance mechanism referenced during signup flows.

Goals
- Present platform terms of use, governing law, liability, and service-level notes in a clear, scannable format.
- Provide a legally binding, readable document with structured sections and navigable anchors.
- Ensure accessibility, responsive behavior, and print/export readiness (PDF-friendly layout).
- Support easy content updates and versioning; expose effective date and contact information.
- Integrate with design-system UI primitives and the existing Archject visual language (colors, typography, spacing).

---

## Page Description (Full Detail)
[MANDATORY: Provide a detailed page description immediately after Overview. Include what this page is, its goals, connected features, UI elements & visual guidance, and API integrations. Use the details provided in PROJECT CONTEXT.]

- Page purpose: A standalone Terms of Service document page that communicates:
  - Platform terms of use (permitted actions, user responsibilities, IP rights, license limitations, etc.).
  - Governing law and jurisdiction.
  - Liability limitations and disclaimers.
  - Service-level notes (uptime expectations, maintenance windows, support commitments, and any notice periods).
  - Effective date, last updated date, and contact information for inquiries.
- Structure:
  - Hero header with page title “Terms of Service” and effective date.
  - Table of contents with anchor links to major sections (Usage, Prohibited Actions, Intellectual Property, Liability, Service Levels, Indemnification, Governing Law, Dispute Resolution, Modifications, Termination, Contact).
  - Legally formatted content sections with clearly defined headings, paragraphs, and any bullet lists.
  - A conspicuous, non-intrusive “Accept/Consent” mechanism reference for signup (informational note that consent is captured during signup) and a separate “Export” option to print/export the page as PDF.
  - Footer with version/date stamps and contact/legal notice.
- UI/UX guidance:
  - Typography: long-form readability, comfortable line lengths, generous line-height.
  - Card-free main content surface but can use subtle section dividers and anchors for accessibility.
  - Visual guidance should align with the following visual style: clean, minimal, with white space; content remains primary; no distractions.
  - Accessibility: WCAG 2.1 AA compliant, semantic headings, ARIA landmarks, keyboard navigable, proper focus order.
  - Print/export: The page should render cleanly to PDF with fixed header/footer and page breaks suitable for legal documents.
- API integrations:
  - No external API connections for this page in its basic rendering. Content should be statically stored with versioning support in the CMS/DB (see Data Models).
  - If content is edited, trigger a content versioning workflow and surface last updated date automatically.
- Content management:
  - Templates and content blocks should be modular to allow easy updates by legal/compliance teams.
  - A field for effective date, last updated date, and version number (auto-increment on edits).
- Localization readiness:
  - Prepare strings and layout to support translations without breaking layout (RTL/LTR considerations if required later).

---

## Components to Build
- TermsOfServicePage component
  - Subcomponents:
    - HeroHeader: Title, EffectiveDate
    - TableOfContents: Interactive anchor-based navigation
    - SectionRenderer: Renders each content block (Heading + Paragraphs + Lists)
    - AcceptConsentNote: Non-functional on this page but references signup consent mechanism
    - ExportPanel: PDF/Print button, preview modal if needed
    - VersionBar: LastUpdated, VersionNumber, LegalContact
  - Data-driven: Content blocks sourced from a structured document model (sections, subsections, bullets, links)
- LegalDocumentTemplateTemplates (asset)
  - Template content for:
    - Privacy Policy
    - Terms of Service
    - Exportable Decision Log cover pages (for PDF exports)
  - Each template should include placeholders for project name, effective date, version, and company branding.
  - Export logic to generate a PDF with consistent header/footer, page breaks, and page numbering.

---

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Page layout
  - Full-width hero area with title and date.
  - Left-aligned, readable content surface divided into semantic sections.
  - Table of Contents with sticky behavior on tall content (optional) and smooth scrolling to anchors.
  - Export/Print controls prominently placed in a card with subtle shadow.
- UI Components
  - Typography: Use Inter/SF Pro/Manrope-like sans-serif with 400/500/600 weights as specified.
  - Headings: H1 for page title, H2/H3 for sections, with consistent spacing (8px increments).
  - Lists: Bullet and numbered lists with clear indentation and spacing.
  - Anchors: Visible focus rings for keyboard navigation.
  - Buttons: Print/Export as primary action (soft outline or filled depending on design): prefer a subdued action style for legal content; consider a small print icon.
  - Links: Underlined or high-contrast to indicate external/legal references.
  - Accessibility: ARIA roles for landmark regions; landmark roles for main content; descriptive link text.
- Visual styling
  - Card usage should be minimal for the page content; if sections are card-like, apply subtle borders or shadows per design system.
  - Color usage: Text primary dark gray (#23272F); links in a muted accent color; no strong color emphasis on heavy legals beyond status or alert indicators (if used).
  - Shadows and borders: Light shadows (#E6E8F0) and borders (#D1D5DB) as separators.
- Interactivity
  - Smooth scroll to anchors; highlight active section in the TOC as the user scrolls.
  - Print/Export button triggers a print dialog or server-side PDF export endpoint (see API).
- API Integrations
  - None required for runtime fetch; content stored in CMS or content store. Prepare endpoints for content retrieval if a headless CMS is used (e.g., GET /legal/terms?version=...).

### Backend
- Data Models
  - LegalDocument
    - id: string
    - name: string (e.g., "Terms of Service")
    - version: int
    - effectiveDate: date
    - lastUpdated: date
    - sections: array of Section
    - brandingMeta: Branding info (logo URL, company name)
  - Section
    - id: string
    - title: string
    - contentBlocks: array of ContentBlock
  - ContentBlock
    - type: enum [paragraph, list, subheading, link, blockquote]
    - content: string (for paragraph/text)
    - bulletPoints: array<string> (for lists)
    - links: array<Link> (optional)
  - Link
    - text: string
    - href: string
  - Template
    - id: string
    - name: string
    - contentStructure: as LegalDocument with placeholders
- API Endpoints (optional for CMS-driven setup)
  - GET /legal/terms/latest
    - Returns current Terms of Service document
  - GET /legal/templates/privacy
  - GET /legal/templates/terms
  - POST /legal/documents/:id/versions
    - Create a new version after edits (admin/legal role required)
  - GET /legal/documents/:id/export/pdf
    - Generate and return a PDF export (server-side rendering with consistent header/footer)
- Export/Print service
  - A server-side PDF renderer (e.g., headless Chrome or PDF library) that consumes the document model and produces a well-formatted PDF with:
    - Header: Company branding, document name, version
    - Footer: Page numbers, date
    - Content: Structured sections with proper page breaks
  - Ensure export uses the same content blocks in a printable layout and supports an export-safe subset (no interactive elements)

### Integration
- Content source: The Terms of Service content is sourced from a structured legal document model (CMS or DB). The frontend fetches the latest version via GET /legal/terms/latest.
- Versioning: When legal edits occur, a new version is created via /legal/documents/:id/versions; the frontend should show the current effectiveDate and lastUpdated.
- PDF Export: Frontend triggers /legal/documents/:id/export/pdf; the backend generates a printable PDF and returns a download URL or binary content.
- Localization: Prepare the API to surface locale-specific content if localization is introduced; the UI should switch strings via locale keys.

